    <item>
      <title>Creating Proxmox VM with Terraform</title>
      <link>/posts/terraform_proxmox/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 07 Aug 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>/posts/terraform_proxmox/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;prerequisites&#34;&gt;Prerequisites&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I assume you have Proxmox already installed and you know how to create VM in cloud using terraform&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;creating-vm-template&#34;&gt;Creating VM template&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;You need VM template for creating vm&amp;rsquo;s with terraform&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;get-standard-installation-iso-image&#34;&gt;Get standard installation ISO image&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;for this example we will use debian netinst iso.&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.debian.org/distrib/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;link to debian page&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;you can dowload iso directly to proxmox&#xA;proxmox web ui -&amp;gt; node_name -&amp;gt; Local -&amp;gt; &amp;ldquo;Download from url&amp;rdquo;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;create-standard-vm&#34;&gt;Create standard VM&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;go to proxmox web interface&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Introduction to terraforming clouds</title>
      <link>/posts/introduction_to_terraforming_clouds/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 20 Jun 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>/posts/introduction_to_terraforming_clouds/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;infrastructure-as-a-code---why-terraform-tech-is-great&#34;&gt;Infrastructure as a code - Why Terraform tech is great&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Terraform lets you manage and automate your infrastructure by writing simple, human-readable code. &lt;br&gt;&#xA;Instead of manually setting up servers, networks, or cloud services, you declare what you want in a configuration file. &lt;br&gt;&#xA;Terraform takes care of creating, updating, or deleting those resources across different platforms, making infrastructure&#xA;management consistent, repeatable, and easy to track. The only thing that I regret about it is that i did not learned it earlier&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Using Jupyer notebook as python application</title>
